{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"38cb397c-5f34-4911-8126-6090dcadbbe2","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here. They only cover **how the .NET runtime is loaded** (e.g., runtime version selection, shim behavior). A `NullReferenceException` is a **managed code bug** — it means your code is dereferencing a null reference at runtime.\n\nTo diagnose this, you'd want to:\n\n1. **Check the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line threw the exception.\n2. **Collect a crash dump** — use `dotnet-dump collect` or `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1`.\n3. **Enable first-chance exception logging** — to catch it before it's unhandled.\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches? If you can share the **stack trace** or an **exception log**, I can pinpoint the null reference.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"969f5e48-279d-49e2-b339-94d2a3b1b6d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which is described as: \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with how the CLR (Common Language Runtime) is loaded and initialized — things like which runtime version is selected, whether the shim picks the wrong runtime, etc. A NullReferenceException is a managed code bug, not a CLR activation problem.\n\n\nI should clarify this distinction for the user and explain why this particular skill won't help solve their issue.","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"418E:D37CE:74AA8A1:8071B66:69F16012"},"id":"ba97e0df-3041-491a-8f69-7dd246314943","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:34:20.907Z","parentId":"a08f6f9e-dd1a-4b32-a9b5-dbe348c59dd0"}
